APPENDIX A AND APPENDIX B
A
Interview 1 of 5 — Security Guard 1
Role: Gate Security Officer
Location: Main Entrance Gate – Al Mouj Muscat
Date: 2 April 2026
Time: 10:00 AM
Interviewer: Ali (Project Group 2, MEC)

Q1: What is your current process for registering visitors to the gate?
A: I ask visitors for their name and the resident they are visiting when they arrive. I make this note in the paper logbook, along with their ID number and the time they arrive. Then I dial through the intercom to check with the resident. The resident sometimes doesn't answer and I have to leave the visitor waiting.

(Q2) How long takes it to process one visitor with the current manual system ?
A: 3-5 minutes on average per visitor. However, many visitors come in at the same time during rush hours such as mornings between 8-9 AM or evenings. The waiting line becomes long and people start complaining about the waiting time.

Q3: Is there any issue you have had with the paper logbook?
A: Yes, many times. Some visitors write their names in Arabic and some in English, and the handwriting is often difficult to read. My memory is very poor when management requires me to pull back a record of visitors from the past, it takes a long time. Also, there were instances of damage or loss of pages.

Q4: How do you currently confirm if somebody was really expected to come by by a resident?
A: The intercom is only used to contact the resident. Previous information of persons attending is not available. We let someone in at times, and then discover that the resident was not expecting them. It's unsafe.

Q5: Do you think a QR code system would aid your work? What features would you want to have?
A: Yes, definitely. Once they register their visitors beforehand and send me a QR code, I scan it and it indicates whether they can get in or not. Would be much quicker. I would also like to have it be able to work on my cell phone since we don't have a computer at the gate.


Interview 2 of 5 — Security Guard 2
Role: Gate Security Officer
Location: Main Entrance Gate – Al Mouj Muscat
Date: 2 April 2026
Time: 10:20 AM
Interviewer: Ali (Project Group 2, MEC)




Q1: What is your existing process for checking in a visitor at the gate?
The visitor tells me their name. I record in the logbook the date and time. Then I call the resident. If the resident confirms I let the visitor in, then I record this. Otherwise the visitor has to wait outside.
Q2: How many minutes does it take to process one visitor with the present manual system?
A: Simple visits take - maybe 2 minutes. But if the resident does not answer the intercom it can take 10 minutes or more. The line fills up very fast during rush hours and it's stressful.

Q3: Have you faced any problems with the paper logbook?
A: The main issue is deciphering the handwriting. They complete their information at times and I don't know what it is. The logbook gets full rapidly as well and we need to create a new one. Access to old records is extremely challenging.
Q4 :Currently, how do you ensure that a resident is receiving a visitor?
A: We only have the intercom! It is impossible to predict whether a visitor will be coming or not in advance. This is a problem particularly at night as residents often aren't quick to respond. We cannot wait too long for people but we cannot have anyone enter without confirmation.

Q5: Would the implementation of a QR code-based system be beneficial to your work? What would you like the features to be?
A: Yes it would be very helpful. If I can scan a QR code and right away get the information of my visitors and their approval status on my mobile device, it saves a lot of time! I do not want to have to log into a computer. It would be great if there was a quick scan at the gate on the phone.



Interview 3 of 5 — Security Guard 3
Role: Gate Security Officer
Location: Secondary Gate – Al Mouj Muscat
Date: 3 April 2026
Time: 11:00 AM
Interviewer: Ali (Project Group 2, MEC)

Q1. How do you currently register a visitor at the gate?
I request identification and his/her name. I make a note of the information in my log book. I then call the resident. When approved I let them in. The entire thing is a paper-based process. We don't have a digital system.
Q3: What is the time required by the manual system to process one visitor?
A: On average approximately 3-4 minutes. However, when there is an event in Al Mouj Muscat, such as Eid or weekends, many people crowd the line and the line gets very long. Manual process is not able to process high volume in a timely fashion.
Q3: Have you had any difficulties with the paper logbook?
A: Yes. Handwriting problem is one of the most frequently occurring problems. Sometimes the log book gets wet due to a spill or rain and is impossible to read. But if someone has visited before we need to do it manually checking all the hundreds of pages.
Q4: What methods do you use to confirm that the visitor is indeed expected by the resident?
A: We call on the resident but often there is no response. We also do not know whether the visitor is being truthful about who he or she is visiting. Occasionally, it has happened that a person has said they were visiting a resident, but the resident didn't recognize him.
Q5: Do you think a QR code system would be useful for your project? What would be your expectations of this?
A: QR system would be awesome. I want to view the code and get the instant feedback whether it's a valid code and who approved it. I also want to automatically have a record of the system without having to write anything. And it has to run on a mobile phone — we don't have computers to play with here.
Interview 4 of 5 — Security Guard 4
Role: Senior Gate Security Officer
Location: Main Entrance Gate – Al Mouj Muscat
Date: 3 April 2026
Time: 11:25 AM
Interviewer: Ali (Project Group 2, MEC)

Q1: What is your current form of verification for visitors at the gate?
A: It's been three years and it hasn't changed here. Visitor comes in, presents ID, I write it in the logbook, call the resident, wait for permission, then open the door to the resident. It's a manual and time consuming process. There are many times that we have said that we need another system.
Q2: What is the time required to process one visitor with the existing manual process?
A: 3-5 minutes on a normal day. However, I have witnessed lines of 10 or more cars when we were only able to cater to one visitor. It's really challenging in the early morning and late evening hours. Some of the delays have been mentioned to management directly by the residents.
Q3: Do you have any issues with the paper logbook?
A: Many problems. The primary one is that the records aren't secure. The logbook is available on the gate for anyone to view. It contains individual details such as visitor names, ID numbers and which apartment the visitor is visiting. From a privacy point of view this is not acceptable. What's more, the writing is also frequently illegible.
Q4: How do you currently verify that someone is really going to visit a resident?
A: Only via the intercom. There have been times when a visitor has stated that he/she was at the residence of a citizen, who was not there, and we were unable to verify. We need a system in place where the person who comes in registers with the resident before they come in in order that we know what to expect when they arrive.
Q5: Would it be beneficial to your work if you were to use a QR code system? What attribute would you desire?
A: Absolutely. The most significant thing to me about pre-registration is that it is pre-registration. If the resident registers the visitor before he/she comes, I scan the QR code; the QR code displays the visitor's details and the visitor's approval; and I open the door within seconds. Also I want the resident to automatically be alerted when their visitor is there so that we don't have to crank up the intercom.
Interview 5 of 5 — Security Guard 5
Role: Gate Security Officer
Location: Secondary Gate – Al Mouj Muscat
Date: 4 April 2026
Time: 10:30 AM
Interviewer: Ali (Project Group 2, MEC)

Q1: How do you register a visitor at your gate?
A: When a visitor comes I record their name, ID number, and which resident they are visiting in the logbook. Record the time of arrival and then contact the resident to verify. Once they have left, I record the time when they went out. It's all done by hand and requires a lot of work from the visitor.

Q2: What is the time it currently takes to process one visitor with the manual process?
A: 3-7 minutes per visitor. The issue is when I can't get in touch with the resident on the intercom. I have to keep trying or ask the visitor to wait. During busy times this creates a big queue and cars block the entrance road.




Q3. Any issues with paper logbook?
A: There's always a problem with the handwriting. It's also challenging for me to keep count of repeat visitors. Visitors who visit many times: If you have visited many times before, I do not have an easy way to check your history. A digital system was able to just search by name or ID and know all of their previous visits up front.
What is the current system for verifying that a visitor is likely to be received by a resident?
A: The intercom call is the only way we use to communicate. There is no advance notification system. Once we have to stand outside the gate for a long time when somebody is coming and the resident is unaware. It is frustrating to the visitor, the resident and it is frustrating to us.
Q5: Would QR code system assist you in your job? What are the features you'd like?
A: Yes, very much. I want to scan a QR code on my phone and instantly receive an answer — either valid or invalid. I also want the system to automatically notify the resident that they have someone in the house if they scan in, so that I don't have to call anyone. It should be easy to use and be compatible with a mobile phone as there are no computers at the gate


